\i \cf2 Facebook, Twitter, and other social networks
\f1\i0 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\f0 \cf0 \
I am not entirely against adding these, but what do they really bring to the experience? Is it necessary or desirable to have these features? I don\'92t see them adding anything to the text, and in fact in some cases they will detract from the experience in jarring ways. There are more analog ways to use them to spread word of mouth, but I have no desire for people to tweet their progress, or engage with their friends in an intrusive way. A Facebook page, Twitter discussion; these are fine ways of using these sites as 
\i tools
\i0 , third-party to the narrative, and not impinging on them. Does integration really lead to wider popularity? I am not so sure. And if it does, I am not sure it will with this piece. This is not \'93audience-friendly\'94. It may be \'93difficult\'94, but this is not an admonition. Digital narratives can succeed where videogames have failed; they need not be afraid of their own shadow.  I am glad that Failbetter wish Twitter and Facebook to be used for themselves.
