\i \cf2 Treating readers in a certain way
\f1\i0 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\f0 \cf0 \
Do not make readers feel stupid. They are vital, and should not be cheated. They should wish to delve into the subjects raised, and find the necessary detail elsewhere. When interacting with them, such interaction should not serve the self, but the story and their intelligence. I am not sure if I am the Eremite, or his successor, or just a researcher in the Institute myself, and should play that role. Everyone gains narrative as currency, as much or as little as they want or are willing to collect, and there is always another floor for them to reach, to become a ceiling. Narrative supports a database of interest. There are more layers between myself and the reader, but the objective should be to maintain a vital link, and make it feel more immediate, for all of the distance. It is also still a question whether players should be led for narrative effect, and whether this is any different from writing that deliberately provokes a biased way of thinking. I disagree with Jonathan Blow who says that this is unworthy. All art provokes emotion, and all artificial art has a message or purpose behind it. I do not want to take their details - in fact, I have a specific storied reason 
